Predicting Mouse Feedback Type Using Brain Activity

Abstract

Understanding neural activity patterns and their role in behavioral decision-making is a fundamental question in neuroscience. In this study, we employ machine learning models to predict feedback_type in mice using principal components derived from large-scale neural recordings. The dataset is based on Distributed Coding of Choice, Action, and Engagement Across the Mouse Brain, which provides detailed spiking activity from multiple brain regions.

Our approach involves preprocessing neural spiking data into time-resolved firing rates, performing Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to reduce dimensionality, and using these principal components as features for classification models. We evaluate multiple machine learning methods, including Random Forest, Support Vector Machines (SVM), and LASSO regression, to determine the most effective predictive model.

Key challenges include class imbalance, where models tend to favor one class over another, leading to poor recall for the underrepresented category. To mitigate this, we utilize Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) analysis and Youden’s J statistic to optimize classification thresholds.

The results highlight the potential for machine learning to decode feedback-related neural signals across brain regions, providing insights into distributed neural representations of behavior. Further improvements can be made by incorporating advanced feature selection techniques and deep learning approaches to enhance classification performance.

Introduction

Questions of Interest

Understanding decision-making in the brain requires studying how multiple brain areas interact, rather than focusing on a single region. The study “Distributed Coding of Choice, Action, and Engagement Across the Mouse Brain” explores how different neural regions collectively contribute to decision-making processes.

How Do Brain Areas Work Together to Form a Decision? - Decision-making is not localized to a single brain area; instead, it emerges from the combined activity of multiple regions. - The study investigates how neuronal spike patterns across different brain areas encode choice, action, and feedback. - By analyzing distributed neural activity, we aim to determine which brain regions are involved in decision-making and how they interact. - We use machine learning to predict feedback type based on neural activity from multiple brain areas.

Real world Motivation and Impact

Decoding brain activity to predict behavioral outcomes has significant implications for:

  • Neuroscience research – Understanding how different brain regions contribute to decision-making.
  • Medical applications – Improving brain-computer interfaces.
  • Artificial intelligence – Enhancing machine learning models that interpret neural signals.

This analysis aims to predict the feedback type of a mouse based on neural activity recorded across all brain areas. The dataset is based from the paper “Distributed Coding of Choice, Action, and Engagement Across the Mouse Brain”.

Problem setup: - Take the 18 sessions and analyze the data using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on neural spike data to reduce dimensionality. - We then combine the PCAs - Use Random Forest and LASSO Regression to build predictive models. - Evaluate model performance using ROC AUC, confusion matrices, and optimal threshold selection. - Explore how different brain regions contribute to prediction accuracy and determine the best classification threshold for optimal results.

Data Source

This project utilizes neural spike data collected from multiple brain areas of mice performing decision-making tasks. The objective is to determine whether we can accurately predict feedback type (reward vs. no reward) based on brain activity patterns.

The dataset originates from the Distributed Coding of Choice, Action, and Engagement Across the Mouse Brain study.

Key Variables: Neural Activity Features: Processed using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to reduce dimensionality. Applying multiple prediction methods such as lasso regression, random forest, SVM. Prediction Matrix & ROC AUC – Evaluated model performance using Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curves and Area Under the Curve (AUC) to measure classification accuracy. Threshold Optimization – Applied Youden’s J statistic to determine the best threshold for classification. Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA) – Used to explore relationships between different sets of brain region activity patterns. Feedback Type: (dependent variable) The target variable representing reward conditions. Brain Areas: (independent variable) Different regions contributing to decision-making.

Understanding Feedback Type in Mouse Decision-Making

  • Mice perform decision-making tasks, where they must make a choice based on sensory stimuli.
  • After making a choice, they receive feedback indicating whether the choice was correct or incorrect (rewarded or not rewarded).
  • This feedback influences future decision-making and learning, helping the mouse adjust its behavior.
  • We use this information, along with brain area neuron spike activity, to determine whether we can accurately predict the feedback type.

Hypothesis

Neural activity patterns from multiple brain areas encode feedback information, allowing us to predict the feedback type (rewarded vs. non-rewarded) with machine learning models.

Background

This study builds upon existing neuroscience research exploring how decision-making processes are distributed across multiple brain areas. Our analysis is based on data from the study “Distributed Coding of Choice, Action, and Engagement Across the Mouse Brain”, which investigates how neural activity across different brain regions encodes behavioral choices, actions, and feedback.

Source of Data - The dataset consists of neuronal spike recordings from mice engaged in decision-making tasks. - Neural activity was recorded from multiple brain regions, capturing how different areas contribute to choice and feedback processing.

Target Population - The target population includes mice performing a behavioral task, where they must make sensory-based decisions and receive feedback (rewarded or not rewarded).

Sampling Mechanism

  • The study uses neuropixels probes to capture spiking activity from neurons across different brain regions.
  • Neural activity is aligned with behavioral events, such as decision-making and feedback reception.
  • The data is structured to allow analysis of how different brain regions work together to encode feedback information.

Explanation of Variables - Predictor Variables – Neural activity from multiple brain areas, reduced to principal components using PCA. - Response Variable – Feedback Type (0 or 1), indicating whether the mouse received a reward.

Existing Research & Literature - Prior studies have focused on individual brain regions—such as the frontal, parietal, and motor cortices, basal ganglia, thalamus, cerebellum, and superior colliculus—recent research suggests that multiple brain areas contribute to decision-making (Cisek2010, Romo2013, Ding2013). - The original study proposes that feedback encoding is not localized to a single brain area, but rather results from network-level interactions. - Our analysis builds upon this research by applying machine learning models to test whether distributed neural signals can be used to predict feedback type.

Exploratory Analysis part 1

Introduction

In part 1 we examine the structure and properties of the dataset of session 1 to build an effective prediction model for mouse feedback type based on neural activity.

We will focus on the following aspects:
1. Data structure across session 1
- Understanding the number of neurons, trials, stimuli conditions, and feedback types recorded across sessions.
2. Neural activity during each trial
- Examining how neurons fire in response to sensory stimuli and decision-making processes.
3. Changes across trials
- Investigating how neural activity evolves over multiple trials within a session.
4. Homogeneity and heterogeneity across sessions and mice
- Analyzing variations in brain activity and behavioral responses across different sessions and individual mice.

Data Structure Across Session 1

  • The dataset consists of 114 trials in session 1.
  • Each trial contains spiking activity from 734 neurons over 40 time bins.
  • The contrast stimuli varied across trials:
    • Contrast Left ranged from 0 to 1.
    • Contrast Right ranged from 0 to 1.
  • Feedback Types:
    • 69 trials resulted in a reward (feedback_type = 1).
    • 45 trials resulted in no reward (feedback_type = -1).

Neural Activity During Each Trial

The neural activity is stored in spks, which is a list of matrices, where: - Rows represent neurons. - Columns represent time bins. - Values are either 0 (no spike) or 1 (spike). - Each trial contains 734 neurons, each responding at 40 different time bins. - Neural activity varies across trials, with some neurons firing more frequently than others. - Some trials show consistent firing patterns, while others exhibit greater variability.

Changes in Neural Activity Across Trials

  • There is high variability in firing patterns across different trials.
  • Certain neurons increase or decrease firing rates depending on feedback type.
  • Across multiple trials, some neurons consistently respond to specific stimulus conditions, while others show trial-to-trial variability.

Homogeneity and Heterogeneity Across Sessions and Mice

  • Some sessions show more uniform responses, while others have greater variability in firing patterns.
  • Some mice display consistent decision-making patterns, while others have more random behavior.
  • There is heterogeneity across mice, meaning not all mice respond in the same way to the same stimulus.

# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 1
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session1.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 1
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
## [1] "ACA"  "MOs"  "LS"   "root" "VISp" "CA3"  "SUB"  "DG"
# Function to process session 1 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 1", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 92
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session1.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

## [1] "CA1"   "VISl"  "root"  "VISpm" "POST"
# Function to process session 2 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

  theme_minimal()

cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session2.csv", row.names = FALSE)

#####################################session 3
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 3
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session3.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 2
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "DG"    "VISam" "MG"    "CA1"   "SPF"   "root"  "LP"    "MRN"   "POST" 
## [10] "NB"    "VISp"
# Function to process session 2 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 180
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session3.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

############################################session 4
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 4
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session4.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 4
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "LGd"  "DG"   "TH"   "SUB"  "VPL"  "VISp" "CA1"  "VISa" "LSr"  "ACA" 
## [11] "MOs"
# Function to process session 4 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

##################################################session 5
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 5
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session5.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 5
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "VISa" "root" "CA1"  "SUB"  "DG"   "OLF"  "ORB"  "ACA"  "PL"   "MOs"
# Function to process session 5 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 6
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session6.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 6
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
## [1] "AUD"  "root" "SSp"  "CA1"  "TH"
# Function to process session 6 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 7
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session7.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 7
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
## [1] "VPL"  "root" "CA3"  "LD"   "CP"   "EPd"  "SSp"  "PIR"
# Function to process session 7 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 7
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 197
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session7.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

##################################session 8
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 8
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session8.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 8
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "ILA"  "TT"   "MOs"  "PL"   "LSr"  "root" "LD"   "PO"   "CA3"  "VISa"
## [11] "CA1"  "LP"   "DG"   "VISp" "SUB"
# Function to process session 8 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 204
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session8.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

################################### session 9
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 9
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session9.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 9
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "TT"    "ORBm"  "PL"    "LSr"   "root"  "CA3"   "VISl"  "CA1"   "TH"   
## [10] "VISam" "VPL"   "LD"
# Function to process session 9 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 293
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session9.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

################################# session 10 
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 10
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session10.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 10
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "MB"    "VISp"  "SCm"   "SCsg"  "POST"  "DG"    "MRN"   "CA1"   "VISl" 
## [10] "POL"   "root"  "GPe"   "VISrl"
# Function to process session 10 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 345
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session10.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

##################################session 11
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 11
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session11.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 11
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
## [1] "MOp"  "LSc"  "root" "PT"   "CP"   "LSr"
# Function to process session 11 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 11", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 255
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session11.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

################################## session 12
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 12
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session12.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 12
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "VISp"  "DG"    "SUB"   "LGd"   "PL"    "root"  "MOs"   "ACA"   "CA1"  
## [10] "VISam" "MD"    "LH"
# Function to process session 12 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 266
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session12.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

###################################### session 13
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 13
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session13.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 13
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "VISam" "ZI"    "DG"    "CA1"   "LGd"   "MB"    "SCs"   "RN"    "MRN"  
## [10] "SCm"   "ACA"   "PL"    "MS"    "root"  "MOs"
# Function to process session 13 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 238
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session13.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

########################################### session 14
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 14
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session14.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 14
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "ORB"  "MOs"  "root" "MRN"  "SCm"  "SCs"  "VISp" "RSP"  "CA1"  "PAG"
# Function to process session 14 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 214
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session14.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

###################################session 15 
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 15
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session15.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 15
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
## [1] "BLA"  "GPe"  "root" "VPM"  "LGd"  "ZI"   "MB"   "CA3"
# Function to process session 15 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 314
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session15.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

##################################session 16
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 16
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session16.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 16
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
## [1] "SSs" "SSp" "MB"  "TH"  "LGd" "CA3"
# Function to process session 16 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 216
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session16.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))
