#####################################session 17 
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 17
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session9.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 17
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "TT"    "ORBm"  "PL"    "LSr"   "root"  "CA3"   "VISl"  "CA1"   "TH"   
## [10] "VISam" "VPL"   "LD"
# Function to process session 17 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 2
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 293
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session17.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

###################################session 18
# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)

# Load the RDS file for session 18
data <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/STA141AProject/data/session18.rds")

# Identify unique brain areas in session 18
unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)
print(unique_brain_areas)
##  [1] "CP"   "ACB"  "OT"   "SI"   "SNr"  "LGd"  "ZI"   "CA3"  "root" "TH"
# Function to process session 18 with only its brain areas
process_session <- function(data, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Check if session contains relevant brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no relevant neurons
  
  # Extract relevant spike data for valid neurons
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])
  
  # Function to compute time-resolved firing rates for one trial
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width = 0.1) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) { 
      bins <- c(bins, end_time) 
    }
    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      window_start <- bins[i]
      window_end <- bins[i+1]
      indices <- which(time_vector >= window_start & time_vector < window_end)
      if (length(indices) == 0) {
        return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      } else {
        return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (window_end - window_start))
      }
    })
    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }
  
  # Apply time-resolved firing rate computation to each trial
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })
  
  # Flatten each trial's matrix (neurons x windows) into a single feature vector
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) {
    as.vector(mat)
  })
  
  # Create a data frame for all trials from this session
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  
  # Extract feedback_type and ensure it's numeric
  if (!"feedback_type" %in% names(data)) return(NULL)
  feedback <- as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type))
  df <- data.frame(feedback_type = feedback)
  
  # Convert trial data to a data frame and assign column names (e.g., "N1_W1", "N1_W2", ...)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])  # Assumes all trials have same number of windows
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))
  
  # Merge feedback_type with the time-resolved features
  df <- cbind(df, trial_df)
  return(df)
}

# Process only session 18
processed_data <- process_session(data)

# Remove constant (zero-variance) columns before PCA
remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
  non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
  return(df[, non_constant_cols])
}

processed_data <- remove_constant_columns(processed_data)

# Perform PCA on the dataset (excluding the feedback_type column)
pca_data <- processed_data[, -1]  # Exclude feedback_type
pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, scale. = TRUE)

# Display PCA summary
summary(pca_result)

# Visualizing the first two principal components
pca_df <- data.frame(PC1 = pca_result$x[,1], PC2 = pca_result$x[,2], feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type)
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = as.factor(feedback_type))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "PCA of Session 2", x = "PC1", y = "PC2", color = "Feedback Type") +
  theme_minimal()

# Determine the number of PCs to explain at least 90% variance
cum_variance <- cumsum(pca_result$sdev^2) / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
num_pcs <- which(cum_variance >= 0.90)[1]
cat("Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance:", num_pcs, "\n")
## Number of PCs needed to explain 90% variance: 174
# Extract the selected principal components
selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:num_pcs])

# Combine the outcome variable with the selected PCs
pca_final_data <- cbind(feedback_type = processed_data$feedback_type, selected_pcs)

# Save the final PCA dataset
write.csv(pca_final_data, "pca_final_data_session18.csv", row.names = FALSE)

# Print dimensions of the new PCA dataset
print(dim(pca_final_data))

Exploratory Analysis 2

Introduction 2 In this section, we conduct further exploratory data analysis by processing neural activity from each session, computing time-resolved firing rates, and applying Principal Component Analysis (PCA)**. The goal is to transform high-dimensional neural spike data into a lower-dimensional space that captures the most relevant patterns while preserving key information.

1 Processing Neural Spike Data First, we load the session 1 dataset and extract: - Unique brain areas in the session. - Spike activity from neurons that belong to these brain areas. - Time-resolved firing rates, computed by binning spike activity into windows of 0.1 seconds.

Steps Taken - Identified valid neurons belonging to recorded brain areas. - Extracted their spiking activity across trials. - Computed firing rates per time window for each neuron. - Flattened the firing rates matrix to create a feature set for each trial. - Extracted the feedback_type variable to use as the target variable.

2 Principal Component Analysis (PCA) After cleaning the data, we applied PCA to reduce the high-dimensional neural data while preserving variance. We took 90% of the variation of the PCA data from each session. Since we need a dataset with the same number of PCAs, we took the maximum amount of PCAs that could be extracted from the smallest session and we took 92PCAs from each session.

Key PCA Steps 1. Standardized the data for mean = 0 and unit variance. 2. Computed principal components, which are linear combinations of the original features. 3. Examined explained variance to determine how many PCs capture most of the information. 4. Took 92 PCAs from session 1-18.

3 Visualizing PCA Results To understand the data in lower dimensions: - We plotted the first two principal components (PC1 vs. PC2). - Points are colored based on feedback type (rewarded vs. non-rewarded trials).

Exploratory Analysis 3: Process of combining the 18 sessions into one

Overview This section details the process of combining the 18 sessions into one

1 Neural Data Preprocessing Loading Data - We load neural spike data recorded from different brain regions for each session. - Brain region labels for neurons. - Spike train data for trials. - Behavioral feedback information (rewarded vs. non-rewarded trials).

Processing Sessions - The function process_session() is used to process each session by: - Identifying unique brain areas in the session. - Filtering out neurons belonging to these brain areas. - Extracting spiking activity for the selected neurons. - Computing time-resolved firing rates, by binning spike activity into 0.1-second windows.

2️ Feature Engineering: Time-Resolved Firing Rates Steps Taken - For each trial: - Neural spiking activity is converted into firing rates over predefined time bins. - These rates are computed for all neurons across all trials. - The firing rate matrix is then flattened into a single feature vector per trial.

3 Applying PCA - Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is used to reduce dimensionality while preserving important neural activity patterns. - 92 principal components (PCs) are extracted per session.

4️ Saving the Processed Data - The processed PCA data, along with feedback type, is saved as: - "pca_final_data_sessionX.csv", where X represents each session number.

5️ Processing All 18 Sessions - The function process_session() is applied to all 18 experimental sessions using: processed_sessions <- lapply(1:18, function(i) process_session(all_sessions[i], i))

##Data intergration method

Justification for using Time-Resolved Firing Rate

Why We Used Time-Resolved Firing Rates Instead of Trial-Averaged Firing Rates

** Problem with Trial-Averaged Firing Rates In my previous coding, firing rates were computed for each neuron by: - Summing all spikes over the entire trial. - Dividing by the total trial duration**.

Issues with This Approach - Loses temporal information: Decision-making and feedback processing occur at specific time points, not uniformly throughout the trial. - Cannot capture dynamic neural patterns: Some neurons increase or decrease activity at key moments, and trial-averaged rates ignore these fluctuations. - Ignores sequence effects: The timing of neural spikes matters, but trial-averaged rates do not capture the order of neural events.

** Why We Used Time-Resolved Firing Rates**

To preserve temporal information, we applied the following method: 1. Divided each trial into predefined time bins (e.g., 100ms windows). 2. Computed the firing rate in each time bin instead of averaging across the entire trial. 3. Flattened the firing rate matrix into a single feature vector per trial.

Advantages of This Approach Captures decision-related dynamics: Neural activity changes over time, and this method detects patterns linked to choice formation and feedback processing.
Improves prediction power: Different brain areas might be more active at certain moments, and this method retains that information.
Maintains temporal resolution: Helps the model learn when neurons fire, which is critical for predicting feedback types.
More interpretable features for machine learning: Instead of a single number, we provide a sequence of firing rate values, making the data richer and more informative.

library(randomForest)

# Load PCA-transformed dataset
pca_data <- read.csv("pca_merged_data.csv")

# Convert feedback_type to a factor
pca_data$feedback_type <- as.factor(pca_data$feedback_type)

# Split the data (80% training, 20% testing)
set.seed(123)
train_index <- createDataPartition(pca_data$feedback_type, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- pca_data[train_index, ]
test_data <- pca_data[-train_index, ]

# Define predictor matrix (X) and response variable (Y)
X_train <- train_data[, -1]
y_train <- train_data$feedback_type

X_test <- test_data[, -1]
y_test <- test_data$feedback_type

# Train Random Forest model
rf_model <- randomForest(x = X_train, y = y_train, ntree = 500, mtry = 5, importance = TRUE)

# Predict probabilities on the test data
rf_probs <- predict(rf_model, newdata = X_test, type = "prob")[,2] 

# Convert -1 to 0 in y_test
y_test <- factor(ifelse(y_test == "-1", "0", "1"))

# Ensure both `y_test` and `rf_pred` have the same factor levels
rf_pred <- ifelse(rf_probs > 0.5, 1, 0)
rf_pred <- factor(rf_pred, levels = levels(y_test)) 

# Compute Confusion Matrix
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(rf_pred, y_test)

# Find the best threshold
results <- data.frame(Threshold = seq(0, 1, by = 0.01), Sensitivity = NA, Specificity = NA, J_statistic = NA)

for (i in 1:nrow(results)) {
  threshold <- results$Threshold[i]
  
  rf_pred_opt <- ifelse(rf_probs > threshold, 1, 0)
  rf_pred_opt <- factor(rf_pred_opt, levels = levels(y_test))
  
  if (length(unique(rf_pred_opt)) > 1) {
    conf_matrix_opt <- confusionMatrix(rf_pred_opt, y_test)
    results$Sensitivity[i] <- conf_matrix_opt$byClass["Sensitivity"]
    results$Specificity[i] <- conf_matrix_opt$byClass["Specificity"]
    results$J_statistic[i] <- results$Sensitivity[i] + results$Specificity[i] - 1
  }
}

# Remove NA rows before selecting the best threshold
results <- na.omit(results)
best_threshold <- results$Threshold[which.max(results$J_statistic)]

# Apply the best threshold
rf_pred_final <- ifelse(rf_probs > best_threshold, 1, 0)
rf_pred_final <- factor(rf_pred_final, levels = levels(y_test))

# Compute Confusion Matrix with best threshold
conf_matrix_final <- confusionMatrix(rf_pred_final, y_test)

# Extract new evaluation metrics
accuracy_final <- conf_matrix_final$overall["Accuracy"]
precision_final <- conf_matrix_final$byClass["Precision"]
recall_final <- conf_matrix_final$byClass["Recall"]
F1_final <- conf_matrix_final$byClass["F1"]

# Plot ROC Curve
plot(roc_obj, col = "blue", main = "ROC Curve - Random Forest with Optimized Threshold")

test_data_new <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/test zip/test/test1.rds")
# Ensure test data is processed similarly to training data
process_test_session <- function(test_data, pca_model, preProc) {
  
  # Extract spike data and compute time-resolved firing rates
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(test_data$spks, function(trial) as.matrix(trial))
  
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix) {
    return(rowMeans(spike_matrix))  # Simplified firing rate computation
  }
  
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(filtered_spikes, compute_firing_rates_time_resolved)
  
  # Convert to data frame
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(do.call(rbind, time_resolved_rates))
  
  # Ensure column names match PCA training data
  colnames(trial_df) <- colnames(pca_model$rotation)  # Ensure correct feature names
  
  # Standardize test data using pre-trained pre-processing object
  trial_df <- predict(preProc, trial_df)
  
  # Apply PCA transformation using the trained PCA model
  pca_transformed <- predict(pca_model, newdata = trial_df)
  
  # Convert PCA result to a data frame
  return(as.data.frame(pca_transformed))
}

# Process the test data
X_test_new <- process_test_session(test_data_new, pca_model, preProc)
## Error: object 'pca_model' not found
process_test_session <- function(data, pca_model, preProc, fixed_pcs = 92, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Identify unique brain areas
  unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)

  # Filter neurons belonging to those brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no valid neurons

  # Extract relevant spike data
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])

  # Function to compute firing rates over time bins
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) bins <- c(bins, end_time)

    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      indices <- which(time_vector >= bins[i] & time_vector < bins[i+1])
      if (length(indices) == 0) return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (bins[i+1] - bins[i]))
    })

    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }

  # Apply firing rate computation
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })

  # Flatten into single feature vectors
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) as.vector(mat))
  
  # Create a data frame for trials
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)

  # Assign column names
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))

  # Remove constant columns
  remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
    non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
    return(df[, non_constant_cols])
  }
  trial_df <- remove_constant_columns(trial_df)

  # Ensure test data has the same column names as the PCA training data
  pca_train_data <- read.csv("pca_merged_data.csv")[, -1]  # Load PCA training data (excluding outcome column)
  required_columns <- colnames(pca_train_data)  # Get required feature names

  # Add missing columns with NA values
  for (col in required_columns) {
    if (!(col %in% colnames(trial_df))) {
      trial_df[[col]] <- 0  # Fill missing columns with 0s (or NA if preferred)
    }
  }

  # Keep only columns that exist in the PCA model
  trial_df <- trial_df[, required_columns]

  # Apply PCA transformation (using pre-trained PCA model)
  pca_transformed <- predict(pca_model, newdata = trial_df)

  # Extract the first 92 PCs
  num_available_pcs <- ncol(pca_transformed$x)
  num_pcs_to_keep <- min(fixed_pcs, num_available_pcs)
  selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_transformed$x[, 1:num_pcs_to_keep])

  # Pad with NA columns if fewer than 92 PCs exist
  if (num_pcs_to_keep < fixed_pcs) {
    padding <- as.data.frame(matrix(NA, nrow = nrow(selected_pcs), ncol = fixed_pcs - num_pcs_to_keep))
    colnames(padding) <- paste0("PC", (num_pcs_to_keep + 1):fixed_pcs)
    selected_pcs <- cbind(selected_pcs, padding)
  }

  # Rename PC columns
  colnames(selected_pcs) <- paste0("PC", 1:fixed_pcs)

  # Apply standardization
  standardized_test_data <- predict(preProc, selected_pcs)

  return(standardized_test_data)
}

# Load PCA Model and Preprocessing Object
pca_model <- prcomp(read.csv("pca_merged_data.csv")[, -1], scale. = TRUE)
preProc <- preProcess(read.csv("pca_merged_data.csv")[, -1], method = c("center", "scale"))

test_data_new <- readRDS("C:/Users/ricky/Desktop/test zip/test/test2.rds")
# Ensure test data is processed similarly to training data
process_test_session <- function(test_data, pca_model, preProc) {
  
  # Extract spike data and compute time-resolved firing rates
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(test_data$spks, function(trial) as.matrix(trial))
  
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix) {
    return(rowMeans(spike_matrix))  # Simplified firing rate computation
  }
  
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(filtered_spikes, compute_firing_rates_time_resolved)
  
  # Convert to data frame
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(do.call(rbind, time_resolved_rates))
  
  # Ensure column names match PCA training data
  colnames(trial_df) <- colnames(pca_model$rotation)  # Ensure correct feature names
  
  # Standardize test data using pre-trained pre-processing object
  trial_df <- predict(preProc, trial_df)
  
  # Apply PCA transformation using the trained PCA model
  pca_transformed <- predict(pca_model, newdata = trial_df)
  
  # Convert PCA result to a data frame
  return(as.data.frame(pca_transformed))
}

# Process the test data
X_test_new <- process_test_session(test_data_new, pca_model, preProc)

process_test_session <- function(data, pca_model, preProc, fixed_pcs = 92, window_width = 0.1) {
  
  # Identify unique brain areas
  unique_brain_areas <- unique(data$brain_area)

  # Filter neurons belonging to those brain areas
  valid_neurons <- which(data$brain_area %in% unique_brain_areas)
  if (length(valid_neurons) == 0) return(NULL)  # Skip if no valid neurons

  # Extract relevant spike data
  filtered_spikes <- lapply(data$spks, function(trial) trial[valid_neurons, ])

  # Function to compute firing rates over time bins
  compute_firing_rates_time_resolved <- function(spike_matrix, time_vector, window_width) {
    start_time <- min(time_vector)
    end_time <- max(time_vector)
    bins <- seq(start_time, end_time, by = window_width)
    if (tail(bins, 1) < end_time) bins <- c(bins, end_time)

    firing_rates_windows <- sapply(1:(length(bins) - 1), function(i) {
      indices <- which(time_vector >= bins[i] & time_vector < bins[i+1])
      if (length(indices) == 0) return(rep(0, nrow(spike_matrix)))
      return(rowSums(spike_matrix[, indices, drop = FALSE]) / (bins[i+1] - bins[i]))
    })

    return(firing_rates_windows)
  }

  # Apply firing rate computation
  time_resolved_rates <- lapply(1:length(filtered_spikes), function(i) {
    compute_firing_rates_time_resolved(filtered_spikes[[i]], data$time[[i]], window_width)
  })

  # Flatten into single feature vectors
  flattened_rates <- lapply(time_resolved_rates, function(mat) as.vector(mat))
  
  # Create a data frame for trials
  trial_df <- do.call(rbind, flattened_rates)
  trial_df <- as.data.frame(trial_df)

  # Assign column names
  num_neurons <- length(valid_neurons)
  num_windows <- ncol(time_resolved_rates[[1]])
  colnames(trial_df) <- paste0("N", rep(1:num_neurons, each = num_windows), 
                               "_W", rep(1:num_windows, times = num_neurons))

  # Remove constant columns
  remove_constant_columns <- function(df) {
    non_constant_cols <- sapply(df, function(col) length(unique(col)) > 1)
    return(df[, non_constant_cols])
  }
  trial_df <- remove_constant_columns(trial_df)

  # Ensure test data has the same column names as the PCA training data
  pca_train_data <- read.csv("pca_merged_data.csv")[, -1]  # Load PCA training data (excluding outcome column)
  required_columns <- colnames(pca_train_data)  # Get required feature names

  # Add missing columns with NA values
  for (col in required_columns) {
    if (!(col %in% colnames(trial_df))) {
      trial_df[[col]] <- 0  # Fill missing columns with 0s (or NA if preferred)
    }
  }

  # Keep only columns that exist in the PCA model
  trial_df <- trial_df[, required_columns]

  # Apply PCA transformation (using pre-trained PCA model)
  pca_transformed <- predict(pca_model, newdata = trial_df)

  # Extract the first 92 PCs
  num_available_pcs <- ncol(pca_transformed$x)
  num_pcs_to_keep <- min(fixed_pcs, num_available_pcs)
  selected_pcs <- as.data.frame(pca_transformed$x[, 1:num_pcs_to_keep])

  # Pad with NA columns if fewer than 92 PCs exist
  if (num_pcs_to_keep < fixed_pcs) {
    padding <- as.data.frame(matrix(NA, nrow = nrow(selected_pcs), ncol = fixed_pcs - num_pcs_to_keep))
    colnames(padding) <- paste0("PC", (num_pcs_to_keep + 1):fixed_pcs)
    selected_pcs <- cbind(selected_pcs, padding)
  }

  # Rename PC columns
  colnames(selected_pcs) <- paste0("PC", 1:fixed_pcs)

  # Apply standardization
  standardized_test_data <- predict(preProc, selected_pcs)

  return(standardized_test_data)
}

# Load PCA Model and Preprocessing Object

Random Forest Model and Threshold Optimization

Overview A Random Forest prediction model was used to predict feedback type based on neural activity.
Additionally, we optimized the classification threshold using Youden’s J statistic to enhance model performance.

Data Preparation and Model Training

Loading and Preprocessing the Data - The dataset, pca_merged_data.csv, contains PCA-transformed neural activity features. - The feedback_type variable is converted to a factor for classification. - The dataset is split into training (80%) and testing (20%) to ensure model generalizability.

Training the Random Forest Model - A Random Forest model is trained using 500 decision trees (ntree = 500) and 5 random predictors per split (mtry = 5). - The model learns to classify feedback type based on PCA features.

Initial Model Evaluation - The model generates probability scores for test data. - Using a default threshold of 0.5, predictions are classified into feedback types. - A confusion matrix and ROC AUC score was used to evaluate initial model performance.

Optimizing the Classification Threshold - The default threshold of 0.5 may not be optimal. - Youden’s J statistic (Sensitivity + Specificity - 1) is computed across multiple thresholds (0 to 1, step 0.01). - The optimal threshold is selected as the one that maximizes Youden’s J statistic. - A new confusion matrix is generated.

Results and Findings - AUC/ROC curve was 0.54. - Accuracy was 0.7103. - There was some error with the code for R markdown for performing Youden’s J statistic but somehow it worked on regular R. In the regular R code the threshold that the Youden’s J statistic produced was 0.7 and the AUC/ROC curve was 0.5

Why We Used Random Forest and Youden’s J Statistic

Why Random Forest? We chose the Random Forest model because: - It is a powerful ensemble learning algorithm that reduces overfitting compared to single decision trees. - It can handle high-dimensional data, making it well-suited for PCA-transformed neural activity features. - It automatically captures non-linear relationships between brain activity patterns and feedback type. - It provides feature importance scores, allowing us to analyze which brain areas contribute most to prediction accuracy.

Justifucations

Addressing the Imbalanced Confusion Matrix - Our confusion matrix was unbalanced, meaning that one feedback type (e.g., rewarded) was predicted much more frequently than the other. - Traditional accuracy measures can be misleading in such cases, as a model might achieve high accuracy by simply predicting the majority class.

Using AUC-ROC for Model Performance - AUC-ROC (Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve) is a robust metric for evaluating model performance in imbalanced datasets. - Unlike accuracy, AUC-ROC evaluates how well the model distinguishes between the two classes across different probability thresholds. - A higher AUC value indicates better discriminatory power between rewarded and non-rewarded feedback.

Using Youden’s J Statistic for Threshold Optimization - Since the default classification threshold of 0.5 did not work well due to class imbalance, we needed to find the best decision threshold. - Youden’s J statistic is a method to find the optimal threshold that maximizes both true positive rate (Sensitivity) and true negative rate (Specificity). - By applying Youden’s J, we selected a better threshold that improved prediction balance and helped correct class imbalance.

Finalization Random Forest was our best model but even with Youden’s J our AUC-ROC was about 0.5 which probably means that it is not a good prediction model.

Test dataset Prediction

The accuracy for my confusion matrix for the test data set was 72%. As you can see on the confusion matrix, there are a lot of true positives being 72. Since our model was also imbalanced towards true positives, it makes sense that the prediction did so well. If we balanced the confusion matrix more, maybe there would be a different output. But due to time constraints, the model was not further investigated.

Test data 2 was also calculated and the accuracy was 73%.

Support Vector Machine (SVM) Summary

The goal of this analysis is to use a Support Vector Machine (SVM) model to predict the feedback type of a mouse based on neural activity. The model is trained on Principal Component Analysis (PCA)-transformed neural spike data and optimized using Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) analysis.

Key Steps in the Analysis 1. Data Preparation
- The dataset is split into 80% training and 20% testing. - The feedback type serves as the target variable. - Principal components (PCs) from neural activity are used as predictors.

  1. Training the SVM Model
    • An SVM with a Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel is trained on the PCA-transformed dataset.
    • The model is configured to output class probabilities.
  2. Making Predictions
    • The model predicts probabilities of class 1 (feedback received).
    • Predictions are converted into binary class labels using an initial threshold of 0.5.
  3. Evaluating Model Performance
    • A confusion matrix is computed to assess accuracy.
    • ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) curve is generated to visualize model performance.
    • AUC (Area Under the Curve) is computed to measure the model’s classification effectiveness.
  4. Optimizing the Classification Threshold
    • Instead of the default 0.5 threshold, we use ROC analysis to determine the optimal decision threshold.
    • The best threshold is selected using Youden’s J statistic, which balances sensitivity and specificity.
  5. Applying the Optimal Threshold
    • Predictions are reclassified using the optimal threshold.
    • A new confusion matrix is computed to reflect the adjusted model performance.
  6. Comparing Different Thresholds
    • Several thresholds (0.1 to 0.9) are tested to analyze how different cutoffs affect predictions.
    • The goal is to identify a balance between sensitivity and specificity.
  7. Visualizing Predictions
    • The ROC curve is plotted to visually assess the trade-off between true positive and false positive rates.

Why We Used Support Vector Machine (SVM)

  1. Handles High-Dimensional Data Well
    • Our dataset contains neural activity features transformed using Principal Component Analysis (PCA).
    • SVM performs well in high-dimensional spaces and avoids the curse of dimensionality.
  2. Works Well with Non-Linearly Separable Data
    • Neural activity patterns are complex and non-linearly separable.
    • The Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel allows SVM to map data into a higher-dimensional space, making it separable.
  3. Robust Against Overfitting
    • SVM maximizes the margin between classes, reducing the risk of overfitting.

Justifucations

SVM had similar issues like random forest Addressing the Imbalanced Confusion Matrix - Our confusion matrix was unbalanced, meaning that one feedback type (e.g., rewarded) was predicted much more frequently than the other. - Traditional accuracy measures can be misleading in such cases, as a model might achieve high accuracy by simply predicting the majority class.

Using AUC-ROC for Model Performance AUC-ROC was used again to model performance instead of just relying on accuracy

Using Youden’s J Statistic for Threshold Optimization Youden’s J statistic helped find an optimal classification threshold

The code in Rmarkdown currently says it has an accuarcy of 1 but previously in regular R it used to be about 70%. # Load necessary libraries
library(glmnet)
library(caret)
library(pROC)

# Read the PCA-transformed dataset
data <- read.csv("pca_merged_data.csv")

# Ensure feedback_type is a factor
data$feedback_type <- as.factor(data$feedback_type)

# Convert feedback_type to binary: Assume original levels are -1 and 1
# Recode -1 as 0 and 1 remains 1
data$feedback_binary <- ifelse(as.numeric(as.character(data$feedback_type)) == -1, 0, 1)
# Ensure feedback_type is a factor
data$feedback_type <- as.factor(data$feedback_type)

# Recode feedback_type: 
# - Keep "1" as 1
# - Convert "0" to 0
data$feedback_binary <- ifelse(data$feedback_type == "0", 0, 1)

# Convert to factor
data$feedback_binary <- as.factor(data$feedback_binary)


# -------------------------------
# Split the Data: 80% Training, 20% Testing
# -------------------------------
set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
train_index <- createDataPartition(data$feedback_binary, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- data[train_index, ]
test_data  <- data[-train_index, ]

# Prepare predictor matrices and response vectors
X_train <- as.matrix(train_data[, !(names(train_data) %in% c("feedback_type", "feedback_binary"))])
y_train <- train_data$feedback_binary  # Keep as numeric 0/1

X_test <- as.matrix(test_data[, !(names(test_data) %in% c("feedback_type", "feedback_binary"))])
y_test <- test_data$feedback_binary  # Keep as numeric 0/1

# -------------------------------
# LASSO Logistic Regression using glmnet
# -------------------------------

y_train <- ifelse(train_data$feedback_type == -1, 0, 1)  # Convert -1 to 0
y_test <- ifelse(test_data$feedback_type == -1, 0, 1)    # Convert -1 to 0



# Perform cross-validation to find optimal lambda
cv_lasso <- cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, family = "binomial", alpha = 1, nfolds = 10)
best_lambda <- cv_lasso$lambda.1se  # Use a slightly larger lambda for more regularization
lasso_model <- glmnet(X_train, y_train, family = "binomial", alpha = 1, lambda = best_lambda)

# Fit the final LASSO model using the best lambda
lasso_model <- glmnet(X_train, y_train, family = "binomial", alpha = 1, lambda = best_lambda)

# Predict probabilities on the test data
test_probs <- predict(lasso_model, newx = X_test, type = "response")

# Convert predicted probabilities to class predictions (threshold 0.5)
test_pred <- ifelse(test_probs > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Convert to factor for comparison
test_pred <- as.factor(test_pred)
y_test <- as.factor(y_test)

# -------------------------------
# Evaluate Model Performance
# -------------------------------
###############################ensure both factors are the same level 
# Ensure both have the same factor levels
test_pred <- factor(test_pred, levels = c(0,1))
y_test <- factor(y_test, levels = c(0,1))

# Now compute confusion matrix
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(test_pred, y_test)
print(conf_matrix)

# ROC Curve and AUC
# -------------------------------
roc_obj <- roc(y_test, as.vector(test_probs))
auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
print(paste("AUC:", round(auc_value, 3)))
## [1] "AUC: 0.5"
# Plot ROC Curve
plot(roc_obj, col = "blue", main = "ROC Curve - LASSO Logistic Regression")

#####################finding the best threshold
library(pROC)

# Define a sequence of thresholds to evaluate
thresholds <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.01)

# Initialize storage for sensitivity and specificity
results <- data.frame(Threshold = thresholds, Sensitivity = NA, Specificity = NA, J_statistic = NA)

for (i in 1:length(thresholds)) {
  threshold <- thresholds[i]
  
  # Convert probabilities to class predictions based on threshold
  test_pred_opt <- ifelse(test_probs > threshold, 1, 0)
  test_pred_opt <- factor(test_pred_opt, levels = c(0,1))
  
  # Compute confusion matrix
  conf_matrix_opt <- confusionMatrix(test_pred_opt, y_test)
  
  # Extract Sensitivity and Specificity
  results$Sensitivity[i] <- conf_matrix_opt$byClass["Sensitivity"]
  results$Specificity[i] <- conf_matrix_opt$byClass["Specificity"]
  
  # Compute Youden's J statistic
  results$J_statistic[i] <- results$Sensitivity[i] + results$Specificity[i] - 1
}

# Find the best threshold based on maximum Youden's J statistic
best_threshold <- results$Threshold[which.max(results$J_statistic)]
print(paste("Best Threshold based on ROC AUC (Youden's J):", best_threshold))
## [1] "Best Threshold based on ROC AUC (Youden's J): 0"
# Plot Youden’s J statistic vs. Threshold
plot(results$Threshold, results$J_statistic, type = "l", col = "blue",
     xlab = "Threshold", ylab = "Youden's J", main = "Optimal Threshold Selection (ROC AUC)")
abline(v = best_threshold, col = "red", lty = 2)

LASSO Regression and AUC-ROC Analysis

In this section, we apply LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator) regression to predict feedback type in mice based on principal components derived from neural activity data. The goal is to identify important features, improve prediction accuracy, and determine the optimal classification threshold.

Data Preparation - The dataset pca_merged_data.csv is loaded - The dataset is then split into 80% training data and 20% testing data to evaluate model performance.

LASSO Logistic Regression - LASSO is a regularized regression method that performs both feature selection and regularization. It helps improve model performance by reducing overfitting and removing unnecessary variables. - We apply cross-validation (cv.glmnet) to determine the optimal lambda parameter (regularization strength). The lambda.1se value is chosen, which provides a slightly more regularized model. - A logistic regression model with LASSO regularization is trained using the selected lambda value. - A threshold of 0.5 is initially used to classify probabilities into rewarded (1) and non-rewarded (0) responses. - Confusion Matrix is computed to evaluate model accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. - ROC Curve and AUC (Area Under the Curve) analysis are used to assess overall model performance.

Justifucations

Why We Used Logistic Regression, LASSO Regression, Youden’s J Statistic, and ROC/AUC

1. Logistic Regression for Classification

##Logistic regression is a statistical model for binary classification problems, where the outcome variable is categorical (e.g., rewarded vs. non-rewarded trials). We chose logistic regression for the following reasons:

  • Baseline Model for Comparison: Logistic regression serves as a good baseline model, helping us assess whether more complex models (such as random forests or SVMs) provide significant improvements.

However, logistic regression can suffer from overfitting when there are too many irrelevant or highly correlated predictors. To address this, we used LASSO regression, a form of regularized logistic regression.

2. Why We Used LASSO Regression LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator) regression is a regularized version of logistic regression. We applied LASSO to improve model performance by selecting the most important features and reducing over fitting. - Handles High-Dimensional Data: Given that we transformed our dataset using Principal Component Analysis (PCA), LASSO helps us identify which principal components contribute most to prediction. - Enhances Interpretability: By shrinking irrelevant features to zero, LASSO makes the model easier to interpret by identifying which features matter the most.

3. Why We Used ROC and AUC the (ROC/AUC) was used again for imbalanced data.

4. Why We Used Youden’s J Statistic We used Youden’s J statistic helps find the optimal threshold for classification when the dataset is imbalanced.

Finalizations We had an accuracy of 0.7077 but our AUC was 0.5. Our confusion matrix was umbalanced. Our Youden’s J was very close to 0 so we coudn’t really find a good threshold because the threshold was so small.

##Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA)

What is CCA? Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA) is a statistical technique used to identify relationships between two sets of variables. It is particularly useful when we want to explore how two different groups of features are related to each other.

Unlike traditional correlation, which measures the relationship between two individual variables, CCA finds linear combinations of variables in each dataset that have the highest correlation with each other.

  • CCA helps us identify relationships between two sets of variables.
  • It helps explore interactions between different brain regions.
  • A high canonical correlation suggests strong connections between two datasets.
  • CCA allowed us to examine how different brain areas contribute to decision-making.

Finalizations CCA was not very useful because there was little to no meaningful correlation between the two sets of variables. Values that are closer to 1 have strong correlation but each of our CCA values were close to 0. We wanted to use CCA to see if the different brain types had some sort of associations with each other.

Disscusion

This study aimed to predict the feedback type in mice based on neural activity across multiple brain regions using machine learning models. By leveraging principal component analysis (PCA) to reduce dimensionality and employing classification models like Random Forest, we sought to decode patterns of neural activity associated with behavioral feedback.

In this project we combined the 18 sessions because we wanted to know if different brain parts were used to help support the decision making process of the mouse for feedback_type.
While in the process of combing the data, we had a problem with Trial-Averaged Firing Rates. In my previous coding, firing rates were computed for each neuron by: Summing all spikes over the entire trial, and Dividing by the total trial duration. We fixed this issue by using Time-Resolved Firing Rates to capture decision-related dynamics, improve prediction power, and maintain temporal resolution.

We then reduced the PCAs to 92 for the data to be smoothly formatted into one dataset.

Different prediction models were used such as random forest, SVM and logistic regression with lasso. Since all of our confusion matrices for the data was imbalanced we needed to rely on AUC/ROC to see which model was the best prediction model, then use Youden’s J statistic to improve class imbalance. Unfortunately, the code for Youden’s J statistic did not transfer well to r markdown from regular R when trying to find a better threshold for SVM and logistic regression. Since these two were unreliable, we used the most reliable model which was the random forest.
The random forest was able to predict the test dataset 1 and 2 with 72% accuracy and 73% respectfully. We used one test data from session 1 and it didn’t really matter which testset we were using because our project was trying to gather information from all the sessions to create a more generalized prediction model to predict either one of the test datasets. Finally, CCA was also used to see if there was any positive relationship between the PCAs. This was placed last because CCA did not find any significant relationship between the PCAs.

Overall, this study demonstrates the potential of machine learning in decoding feedback-related neural signals but also underscores the need for robust data preprocessing, feature selection, and model evaluation strategies to enhance predictive performance.
